Place a lightly oiled #baking sheet{} on top rack (for 4 servings, 2 baking sheets, on top and middle racks) and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; thinly slice crosswise into half-moons. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Zest and quarter @lemon{1} (for 4, zest 1 lemon; quarter both).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1.5%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and cook, stirring, until lightly browned and softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, in a small #bowl{}, combine tomatoes, garlic, and a drizzle of olive oil. Season with salt and pepper.

In a second small bowl, combine @ricotta cheese{4%ounce}, half the lemon zest, @olive oil{0.5%tsp} (1 tsp for 4 servings), and lemon juice to taste. Season with salt and pepper.

Carefully place @flatbreads{2} on prepared sheet (divide between both prepared sheets for 4 servings). Evenly spread flatbreads with lemon ricotta. Top with zucchini and tomatoes, cut sides up. Bake until flatbreads are golden brown, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pick @basil{0.5%ounce} leaves from stems; roughly tear leaves. Once flatbreads are done, remove from oven and top with torn basil, remaining lemon zest, and @chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste. Drizzle with @honey{2%tsp}, then slice into pieces and divide between plates. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> If this recipe could talk, it would say "I'm so fancy!" Seriously: 
> you've got lemony ricotta cheese that's smooth like a cloud, plus 
> bites of tomato and zucchini bursting with juices, which are all piled 
> onto two warm and toasty flatbreads. Oh, and we have to talk about the 
> bling on top: a basil leaf, chili flake, and honey garnish that makes 
> each bite light up with aromatic, spicy, and sweet contrasts. You've 
> just hit dinnertime gold.